Swine diseases increase - Europe 19991104.1977
Swine fever, classical - Germany (Brandenberg) 19990819.1438
Date: 1 Sep 2000
From: Peter Cowen <Peter_Cowen@ncsu.edu>
Source: OIE Disease Information No. 13 Vol 34
<http://www.oie.int/Info/A_info.htm>

CLASSICAL SWINE FEVER IN GERMANY
See also: 19 Nov 1999, 20 Aug 1999, 11 Jun 1999, 28 May 1999
(Date of last previously reported outbreak in domestic pigs: November 1999).
Emergency reports
Text of 2 faxes received on 24 and 31 Jul 2000 from Dr Werner Zwingmann,
Chief Veterinary Officer, Ministry of Food, Agriculture and Forestry, Bonn:
Nature of diagnosis: laboratory.
Dates of initial detection of animal health incidents: 21 and 29 Jul 2000.
Outbreaks:
Location: Bernkastel - Wittlich district, Rhineland - Palatinate Land
No. of outbreaks: 2
Description of affected population: one holding for fattening and one
holding for breeding and fattening.
Total number of animals in the outbreaks:
species/ susceptible/ cases/ deaths/ destroyed/ slaughtered
sui/ 1 045/ .../ .../ 1 045/ 0
Diagnosis:
A. Laboratory where diagnosis was made: State Department for Veterinary
Research, Koblenz.
B. Diagnostic tests used: virus isolation, ELISA (1).
Epidemiology:
A. Source of agent / origin of infection: investigations are under way.
B. Other epidemiological details: the holdings are located in a protection
zone set up because of classical swine fever in feral pigs.
Control measures during reporting period:
- the remaining animals were slaughtered and will be destroyed in rendering
plants;
- prohibition on movements of susceptible animals in an area around the
infected holdings;
- tracing of animal movements into and out of the infected holdings.
(1) ELISA: enzyme-linked immunosorbent assay
